defaultIndividual sectors may present specific 
defaultsectoral
default evidence to the Committee, so this response is centred round more generic issues which we feel are important to ensuring that the whole process of designating and managing MCZs will benefit both conservation and industry, will lead to more effective ways of working and applying regulations and lead to better management of MCZs pre and post designation.
defaultSUDG members played significant roles during the development of the 
defaultpMCZs
default and participated in all four regional projects providing data, information and support to the teams doing the work. SUDG has consistently supported the move to create MCZs and continues to do so. The views of SUDG were made clear in the joint statement that we prepared with the conservation bodies (WCL, MCS, RSPB and the Wildlife Trusts) and presented to Richard Benyon in February 2013. This set out clearly that an essential aspect of good MCZs is a proportionate approach to regulation with clear and practical guidance to meet clear and agreed conservation objectives and management measures. 
defaultThis is a critically important time for marine development and the opportunities to support sustainable development and meet Government policies on economic growth, climate change and environmental protection are enormous. SUDG continues to hold the view that well managed MCZs will not prevent economic growth, but if this is to be the case, and to 
defaultdevelop the broad statements above, a number of important aspects must be clearly recognised and the management of MCZs must show that these points are properly embraced in determining both designation and subsequent management:
